<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by Dr Philip Richens to the Commons Select Committee Inquiry: IPCC 5th Assessment Review</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Dr Philip </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Richens</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> (IPC0021)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">1. I received a PhD in Theoretical Physics in 1982. I  am married, with two grown up children. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2. I wish to address some of the scientific issues raised in the Terms of Reference, and to point out some lines of relevant high quality research inadequately assessed by the report. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">3. My comments are submitted in a personal capacity.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Executive Summar</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">y</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">4. The report does not provide a balanced  assessment of the scientific literature on natural variability. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">5. The report only partially addresses the reliability of climate models.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">6. The report does not sufficiently explain the reasons for the hiatu</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s in global temperature.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">To what extent does AR5 reflect the range of views among climate scientists?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">7. AR5 does not adequately reflect research into longer term natural variability i.e. variability over decadal and longer time scales. The same criticis</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">m applies to AR4. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">8. This criticism can be verified by searching the body of either report for references to [1-9] or to related papers by the same authors. See also {10.7, FAQ 10.1}.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Does the AR5 address the reliability of climate models?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">9. The repor</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">t acknowledges that some climate models simulate too much warming in response to increases in greenhouse-gas concentration {Box TS.3(c), Box TS.4}. This results in a higher estimation of climate sensitivity {Box TS.4} than those based on observation, for e</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">xample [10-11].</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">10. Most models overestimate the warming observed in the tropical troposphere {Box TS.4}.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">11. The global temperature record since the start of the 20th century falls into a series of distinct periods. An </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">early warming</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> during 1910–1940 was followed by a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">mid-century pause</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> when there was little or no trend; a period of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">recent warming</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> started in the mid-1970s and finally there is the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">hiatus</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> in the current century. The magnitudes of the two warming periods are similar, abou</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">t 0.5 degrees C in each case {Figure 2.20, 10.3.1.1.1}.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">12. Most models simulate too much warming during the hiatus when CO2 levels have been high {Box TS.3}, and too little warming during the early warming period when CO2 levels were low {10.3.1.1.3}.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">13. The report's attribution argument is based on comparison between simulations and observation {Box 10.1, FAQ 10.1}. Such a comparison is less convincing when the patterns of decadal variability observed in the instrumental record are not well simulated</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, see also [12]. A dynamical explanation for the differences is not provided.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">14. The question of divergence between model simulated long term variability and variability found in reconstructions [13] is not adequately addressed by the report, see for exa</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">mple {9.5.3.1, Figure 9.33c}. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">15. In model simulations, temperatures tend to track external forcing over decadal and longer time scales, see for example {10.7.1.3}. However, in reconstructions this is not generally the case [14], and this finding is not </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">discussed by the report.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Has AR5 sufficiently explained the reasons behind the widely reported hiatus in the global surface temperature record?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">16. The report suggests that the hiatus "is attributable in roughly equal measure to a cooling contribution fr</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">om internal variability and a reduced trend in external forcing" {Box TS.3(c)}. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">17. [10] states that internal variability is predominantly responsible not only for the hiatus, but also for the early warming and subsequent pause during the first 70 years of the 20th century i.e. all decadal variability from the start of the 20th centur</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">y </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">except </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the recent warming period.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">18. Neither the report nor [10] offers a dynamical explanation for the internal variability responsible (in part) for the hiatus. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">19. The stadium wave is a dynamical mechanism proposed by the line of research describe</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">d in [3] and [15], which explains the hiatus as well as </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">all </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">20th century decadal variability . </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">20. The stadium wave is observed in nature but is not simulated by current climate models [15]. Their analysis suggests that the hiatus may continue into the 2</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">030s. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">References</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">1. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Lennartz</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, S., and A. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Bunde</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. "Trend evaluation in records with long-term memory: Application to global warming." Geophysical Research Letters 36.16 (2009): L16706.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2. Lovejoy, S., and D. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Schertzer</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. "Low-Frequency Weather and the Emer</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">gence of the Climate." Extreme Events and Natural Hazards: The Complexity Perspective (2012): 231-254.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">3. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Tsonis</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, A. A., and K. L. Swanson. "Review article" On the origins of decadal climate variability: a network perspective"." Nonlinear Processes in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Geophysics 19.5 (2012): 559-568.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">4. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Markonis</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Yannis</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-si